## R7 — Structural competition from platforms that already have the data

**What it is**

Google, Amazon, and Meta already hold cross-domain behavioral data about their own users and have not unified it into a "personal decision engine." This is evidence the problem is structurally hard — internal business silos, regulatory exposure, public trust risk — not evidence the opportunity is simply unclaimed.

**Why it matters**

If we succeed at building real cross-domain signal and it becomes commercially interesting, it becomes interesting to platforms with orders of magnitude more data and distribution than us.

**How we would detect it**

Ongoing competitive monitoring once any traction appears.

**What would reduce it**

Depth in a narrow, defensible niche rather than breadth across many domains, at least until there is real traction to defend.

**Status:** Background risk, low urgency now, high urgency if R3 and R6 are resolved positively.

---

## R8 — Privacy and profiling exposure (GDPR)

**What it is**

The core long-term asset — a unified behavioral model of a person across unrelated domains — is, under GDPR, profiling in one of its most sensitive forms.

**Why it matters — but why it's not top of the list**

If nobody wants to use the product at all (R0), this risk never becomes relevant, and legal consultation is comparatively cheap once there's real traction to justify it. It does not need to be resolved before validating demand. But it is not purely a "later" concern either: it becomes an active gate at one specific, predictable moment — the point at which data from two domains is first merged for the same user, which is also the exact moment R6 gets tested.

**How we would detect it**

Not something to wait to "detect" reactively — it needs review at that specific gate, not after.

**What would reduce it**

A single rule tied to a trigger, not a calendar date: before merging any user's data across two domains for the first time (i.e., before testing R6), get at least a basic legal review and design that merge as opt-in per domain rather than a default unified profile.

**Status:** Deprioritized for now by design, re-activates automatically at the R6 test.

---

## R9 — Part-time execution risk

**What it is**

All of the above has to be resolved with 15h/week per person, alongside full-time jobs. This is not a risk specific to PDE, but it compounds every other risk on this list.

**Why it matters**

Every week spent without new evidence (usage data or user conversations) is a week where the biggest risks on this list remain exactly as uncertain as they are today.

**How we would detect it**

Track weeks-since-last-new-evidence as a simple internal metric. If this number keeps growing, something on this list is being avoided.

**What would reduce it**

A hard rule: each 2-week cycle must produce at least one piece of new evidence (a user conversation, a usage metric, a test result) — not just a new document.

**Status:** Ongoing, structural, will not go away.

---

## How to use this document

Before writing PRODUCT.md or MVP.md in detail, resolve R0, R1 and R2 with real user conversations — they determine whether there's a problem worth solving, what frequency it lives at, and what shape of product it needs. Only after that does R3 (the sensor/product paradox) become the right thing to focus execution on.

